    "description": "I went to Palo Alto Wetland Preserve and saw the American Avocets. I like them because of their long black and curved beak, and their unique feathers. In my opinion, these birds are very graceful, for their thin legs that walk slowly in the shallow water. Many other waders do that too!\n\nAmerican Avocets have a special method for eating. They swing their long, thin and curved bill in the water. As they do that, they also scoop up tiny shrimp and fish. In my opinion, that is a very unique eating method.\n\nThe American Avocet has a brown white wing and their tails are gray, black and white. Their heads and plumages are white, —well, usually— their bills are black and slightly curved up and the tip, and their legs are pastel gray-blue, which gives them their colloquial name, Blue Sharks.\n\nDuring the American Avocets breeding season, which is April to June, their plumage turns into a rusty orange color! Then after their breeding season, those feathers are replaced by grayish-white colored ones. That’s one of the biggest reasons why I like the American Avocet.\n\nThe American Avocet’s biggest threat is the loss of wetlands caused by climate change. Another threat is pesticides leaching into the wetlands. The toxic chemicals are very harmful to all wildlife. And the chemicals also mix in with the wetlands and affect feeding birds and nest success too!\n\nAmerican Avocets are not endangered. In fact, they have been increasing during the recent decades. But that doesn’t mean that humans shouldn’t help them! So, people still can help these interesting birds by stopping the air pollution (that causes the climate change) and also stop using the pesticides and find a different way for pest control. This will not only help the American Avocets, but it will also help lots of other animals!",
