    "quickFact": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw Cooper's Hawk.",
    "description": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw Cooper's Hawk. The Cooper’s Hawk is found year round in all of the Bay Area. One distinctive fact about the Cooper’s Hawk is that its tail is more square at the bottom instead of round. Using that fact, I was able to identify the Cooper’s Hawk I saw on my way to tennis class! It was perching on the power line. Now you know how to identify a Cooper’s Hawk!\n\nCooper’s Hawks feed by looking and listening for prey in a dense cover, moving from perch to perch. After they ring their prey, they put on a burst of speed to catch the prey. Sometimes, they hunt low over the ground. Then they approach from behind shrubs and other plants, surprising their prey. Cooper’s Hawks eat mostly small birds like European Starlings, Mourning Doves, Rock Pigeons, American Robins, Northern Flickers, quails, pheasants, grouse, chickens, and several types of jays. They also might eat small mammals such as chipmunks, hares, mice, and bats. Cooper’s Hawks in the west are more commonly found eating mammals.\n\nMale Cooper’s Hawks are 14.6 inches to 15.3 inches in length, and weigh 7.8 ounces to 14.5 ounces. Their size is similar to a crow, a Mallard Duck, or a Herring Gull. They have a wingspan of 24.4 inches to 35.4 inches, which is similar to a Broad-winged Hawk. Female Cooper’s Hawks have a length of 16.5 inches to 17.7 inches. They weigh 11.6 ounces to 24.0 ounces and have a wingspan of 29.5 inches to 35.4 inches.\n\nAn interesting fact about the Cooper’s Hawk is that they tend to capture prey with their feet and squeeze it to death. They hold prey away from their body and squeeze until their catch is dead, unlike falcons, who kill their prey by biting it. Some Cooper’s Hawks and other hawks species even drown their prey by holding it under water until it stops breathing and dies.\n\nIf you have a bird feeder in your backyard, you might attract the attention of a Cooper’s Hawk, given that they eat smaller birds. So unless you want to see the smaller birds being killed and eaten, you should probably take your feeder down for a couple days. Then the hawk will move on.\n\nCooper’s Hawks are pretty common. Their population increased from 1966 to 2019. During the mid-twentieth century, this hawk's stable population decreased due to the use of pesticide DDT (dichloro-diphenyl-trichloroethane). 70% of death in the urban areas is because of collisions with human-made objects like windows and cars. Up to one million Cooper’s Hawks die every year in the United States alone because of collisions.\n\nTo help Cooper’s Hawks, you can use less glass and watch out when driving! In other words, try not to crash into a Cooper’s Hawk, or even better, any bird (or maybe even any type of animal) when driving! Even though their population is very stable, we should still protect Cooper’s Hawks. And plus, if they become extinct, we’ll lose an animal to eat mice (though a lot of smaller birds and small mammals like hares and chipmunks will be saved), and who likes mice? So keep this species protected!",
