    "description": "I went to Shoreline Park and saw the Green-Winged Teal. The Aleutian Islands of Alaska have their own race, called Anas crecca nimia. Unlike the other Green-Winged Teal, this race doesn’t migrate. Instead, they go to ponds and lakes on the island’s beaches where they forage tide pools and sometimes shallow-water reefs. Let’s dig (or I should say fly) in!\n\nGreen-Winged Teals, like all other dabbling ducks (also known as puddle ducks), eat by dabbling, which is obvious because they are called dabbling ducks (I don’t know why they are called puddle ducks so don’t ask me about that). They eat on shorelines, in shallow waters, on agricultural fields, and mudflats. Green-Winged Teals eat sedge fruit, seeds of pondweeds, grasses, smartweeds, sea purslane, bulrush, dwarf spikerush, swamp timothy, corn, rice, midges, tadpoles, molluscs, and crustaceans. Others include worms, seed shrimp, and copepods.\n\nAn interesting fact about the Green-Winged Teal is that it is the smallest dabbling in the world! (To be specific, the males are because they are smaller than the females). And the fastest record of a Green-Winged Teal is 60 miles per hour! A Green-Winged Teal has a length of 12.2–15.3 in (31–39 cm) and weighs 4.9–17.6 oz (140–500 g). They also have a wingspan of 20.5–23.2 in (52–59 cm).\n\nGreen-Winged Teals are quite common. Their population increased during 1966 and 2019. Most of the population breeds in Canada and Alaska because relatively remote and inaccessible nesting areas buffer this species from habitat losses farther south caused by agricultural and urban development. Sadly, about 1.2 to 1.4 million Green-winged Teal were shot in the U.S. in 2019 and 2020. Bag limits for ducks are changed annually based on population size estimates and harvest objectives, helping to safeguard these species against declines. So the only threat that these birds face is hunting pressure. They are a very popular species taken by hunters each year in the USA. According to Partners in Flight, the North American breeding population of the Green-winged teal is 6,700,000 breeding birds. So to help Green-Winged Teals, please don’t shoot them! Even though Green-Winged Teals are widespread and quite common, they are still unique birds and I hope like me, you agree that they should thrive!",
