    "quickFact": "I went to Baylands Nature Preserve and saw the Snowy Egret and the Great Egret.",
    "description": "I went to Baylands Nature Preserve and saw the Snowy Egret and the Great Egret. At first, I thought they were the same type of bird. But when I looked at them through my binoculars, I could tell that they were different species of birds. The Snowy Egret has a black beak, and yellow feet, meanwhile, the Great Egret has a yellow beak, and black feet. The Snowy Egret is also smaller than the Great Egret. The Snowy Egret and the Great Egret have different eating methods too. While the Snowy Egret paddles its feet in the water, finds its prey, captures it and eats it, the Great Egret wades in the water, waits for its prey to come near it, then catches it and eats it.\n\nSnowy Egrets are mostly white. They have a white body, (not counting their legs and feet), black bills and legs with a yellow patch around their eyes. They also have yellow feet. Snowy Egrets have a length of 20 to 27 inches and a wingspan of 41 inches.\n\nSnowy Egrets eat mostly fish, frogs, crustaceans, insects, and worms. They can eat while they run, hop, stand, or walk. Snowy Egrets may also vibrate their beaks, sway their heads, and flick their wings as they gather their prey.\n\nDuring their breeding season which is mid-April to September, the Snowy Egrets head, neck, and back develop long feathers. The area that is between their beaks and eyes turn red. Snowy Egrets breed in central Oregon, central California, and discontinuous zones and pockets of some western states of Idaho, Montana, Wyoming, South Dakota, Nevada, New Mexico, Utah, and Arizona.\n\nSince Snowy Egrets grew long, wispy feathers during their breeding season, people in 1886 would kill them for those feathers which cost $32 each ounce! Because of that, Snowy Egrets got endangered! But in the early twentieth century, early conservationists were able to keep Snowy Egrets alive! After that, Snowy Egrets became common, and are found mostly in marshes.\n\nThe loss of trees for Snowy Egrets to nest in is a major threat to them. Humans that are clearing their habitat, diversification to the hydrology of wandering around in areas, and oil spill impacts to particular breeding, foraging, and roosting sites is also a threat.\n\nEven though Snowy Egrets are low in conservation, we still have to help them if we want them to thrive. So here are some ways you can help them. Stop clearing their habitat, stop foraging in their areas, and don’t spill oil. Then most importantly, don’t kill them for their feathers they have when it’s their breeding season. Snowy Egrets are interesting types of birds, and they deserve to be well cared for by humans.",
