    "quickFact": "As you should know, cheetahs are the world’s fastest land animal, and can reach 70 miles per hour when they run.",
    "description": "As you should know, cheetahs are the world’s fastest land animal, and can reach 70 miles per hour when they run. But can you guess how fast the Peregrine Falcon can dive? They can reach the speed of 240 miles per hour, which is more than three times as fast as the cheetahs! In fact, they are the fastest animal on Earth!\n\nThe Peregrine Falcon eats in a very interesting way. Once they have found their prey, they dive from 300 to 3,000 feet above their prey, and they tuck their wings in. Then they dive down and capture their prey with their sharp talons, though they sometimes miss and they would have to dive again but they usually would hit their prey to make them dizzy, then strike. Peregrine Falcons eat songbirds, ptarmigan, ducks, grebes, thrushes, gulls, longspurs, shorebirds, waxwings, buntings, larks, starlings, pigeons, storm-petrels, bats, rodents, and fish.\n\nPeregrine Falcons have blue-gray wings, a black top of their head and around their eye, a white face, a white and dark-brown chest, and a gray and white underwing. Peregrine Falcons have a length of 1.5 feet and a wingspan of 3.5 feet.\n\nPeregrine Falcons have three eyelids to keep their eyes safe and moisturized. That third eyelid is see through, so that Peregrine Falcons can see while the eyelid is closed! That’s one reason why I like them.\n\nPeregrine Falcon threats are pesticide poisoning, habitat loss, shooting, and taking their eggs and chicks. In the 1940s, the Peregrine Falcon almost became extinct in North America because of the use of DDT (dichloro-diphenyl-trichloroethane)as insecticides. In 1970, they were included in the Endangered Species Act. Their population grew back because of great conservation efforts, and they got removed from the list in 1999.\n\nEven though Peregrine Falcons are of low concern, humans can still help them! So, here are some things you can do for them: stop using pesticides and use other things to kill pests-things that are not harmful, stop destroying their habitat, stop shooting, and don’t take their eggs and chicks (Well, that’s obvious)! Peregrine Falcons are interesting birds, and I hope they will someday be appreciated by everyone!",
