    "description": "I went to Baylands Nature Preserve and saw the Great Blue Heron. I like how they walk slowly and gracefully through the calm water or dry stalks of grass. (usually near the edge of the water.)\n\nThe Great Blue Heron eats by standing as still as a statue, looking in the water for prey, then…snap!!! They catch their prey the instant they bend their neck low and when they are focusing only on it. They usually do this in shallow water or on the shore in marsh grass. They never go too far from the water. Great Blue Herons eat reptiles, fish, small mammals, amphibians, insects, and other small birds.\n\nGreat Blue Herons have blue-gray plumages and bodies, black on the top of their heads, lavender-mauve legs, and a white head. They are 4 feet tall and their wingspan is 6 to 7 feet.\n\nEven though Great Blue Herons are so large, they weigh only 5 to 6 pounds! That’s because of their hollow bones that all birds have. Hollow bones help make birds lighter so it is easier for them to fly.\n\nTraffic, motorboats, and logging are a big threat to Great Blue Herons because they can disturb nesting colonies. Chemical pollutants and other reasons why water reducing qualities happen are also a threat to them.\n\nEven though Great Blue Herons are not endangered, humans can still help them! So here are some ways you can help them: stopping traffic along the wetlands, not having a lot of motorboats, (but of course there can be some), stop logging because Great Blue Herons nest on trees, which if they fall, they can get seriously injured or die. Stopping chemical pollutants will help not the Great Blue Heron but also a variety of other animals! The Great Blue Heron is an interesting bird, and I know that they should get well protected.",
