    "name": "White-Faced Ibis",
    "documentTitle": "Ibis (White-Faced Ibis)",
    "slug": "white-faced-ibis",
    "createdAt": "2026-07-12",
    "habitat": "Wetlands, marshes, ponds, and shorelines",
    "size": "Length 18.1-22.1 in; wingspan about 37-39 in; bill 6-7 in.",
    "color": "Glossy dark ibis with long curved bill; breeding adults show a white face border.",
    "commonness": "Not endangered; population increased about 2.8% per year from 1968 to 2017.",
    "quickFact": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw the White-Faced Ibis.",
    "description": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw the White-Faced Ibis. White-Faced Ibises, like some other species of birds, collect found objects that sometimes include human things like cigarette lighters, empty shotgun shells, plastic dolls, and hair combs. Let's learn!\n\nThe White-Faced Ibis wades in shallow waters, wetlands, or moist soil. They eat earthworms, crustaceans (particularly crayfish), spiders, snails, clams, leeches, and various insects and their larvae (including dragonflies, crickets, grasshoppers, midges, beetles, flies, and other bugs). They have sensitive beaks that help to find prey as well as scanning the water’s surface they might see. They may also open their bills slightly and then swish their bills in the water, snatching anything they can. This method stirs up small aquatic creatures like insects, crustaceans, and small fish that might be moving in the water. They will probe the mud for insects hiding in the mud too. More about their bills is in the fourth paragraph.\n\nWhite-Faced Ibises have a length of approximately 18.1-22.1 inches (46-56 cm), a wingspan of about 37-39 inches (94-99 cm). Their bill is 6-7 inches long (15-18 cm). They weigh 1-1.2 pounds (450-525 grams).\n\nThe White-Faced Ibis has a very sensitive beak (as mentioned before). Their beaks can detect movement through the water which tells the ibis how far, big, deep, and other things like that about whatever it sensed. Sensitive nerve endings are on the beaks, allowing them to do this. They may also probe in the mud under the water to look for anything the tip of their bills touch or sense. The probing method is mainly used for finding insect larvae.\n\nWhite-Faced Ibises are not endangered. In fact, their population increased about 2.8% per year between 1968 to 2017! Threats include pollutants and toxic materials such as heavy metals, organochlorine and other pesticides, and selenium has been found in eggs and adults which is bad for them. These materials have caused mortality or have reduced nesting success. Human disturbance at nesting colonies has caused abandonment, and the species is very sensitive to changes in both foraging and nesting areas. Diversion of water for irrigation and other uses has resulted in the abandonment of traditional colony sites in the U.S.\n\nTo help these species survive, you can stop using pollutants and toxic materials and don’t disturb nesting colonies. Also, don’t irrigate water. Even though White-Faced Ibises are far from extinction, we should still protect this species!",
