    "color": "Blue crest with long black-and-blue feathers.",
    "commonness": "Not endangered and quite common.",
    "quickFact": "Steller’s Jay is named after Georg Steller, not the word “stellar.”",
    "description": "I like the Steller’s Jay because I think it is very pretty. With its blue crest and long black and blue feathers in a neat pattern, this species has a natural grace. When it flies, it looks especially graceful, though its walking can look a little clumsy.\n\nThe Steller’s Jay forages around and eats insects, seeds, berries, nuts, small animals, eggs, and nestlings. It has also been found eating trash and unguarded picnic items. As an omnivore, it also eats peanuts, acorns, pinyon pine seeds, sunflower seeds, and suet from feeders. For winter preparations, the Steller’s Jay buries pinyon pine seeds and acorns along with other nuts in the ground to dig up afterwards.\n\nSteller’s Jays are 30-34 cm (12-13.5 in) long, weigh 100-140 g (3.5-4.9 oz), and have a wingspan of 44-48 cm (17.3-19 in).\n\nDid you know that Steller’s Jays are probably one of the most commonly misspelled names in birdwatching? Looking at the streaks of black and blue, you might think that their name comes from “stellar.” The true reason behind their name is that this species was discovered on an Alaskan island in 1741 by Georg Steller. Scientists later named it after him.\n\nSteller’s Jays are not endangered and are quite common. Threats include habitat loss due to development, collisions with glass, poisoning from pesticides, predators like cats and large raptors, and competition for food with invasive species.\n\nPeople can help Steller’s Jays by protecting habitat, using less glass or bird-safe windows, avoiding pesticides, and keeping pet cats watched or indoors.",
