    "color": "Blue, gray, and white jay with a long tail.",
    "commonness": "Not endangered and quite common.",
    "quickFact": "California Scrub-Jays can crack acorns by holding them with their feet and using both parts of the bill.",
    "description": "I chose the California Scrub-Jay because it visits my bird feeder in the backyard quite often. These birds can be very noisy. I once woke up to one perched on the electrical wire in front of my house, screeching so loudly that I could hear it through my closed bedroom window.\n\nCalifornia Scrub-Jays eat by hopping around on the ground and foraging. They are omnivores and eat mostly insects and fruit during spring and summer, but nuts and seeds during the winter. Other foods include acorns, grass seeds, sunflower seeds, peanuts, cultivated corn, cherries, walnuts, and almonds. To crack an acorn, a California Scrub-Jay holds the nut between its feet, pecks at it with its bill, then uses the lower bill and upper bill to split the crack wide enough to fish out the inside and eat it.\n\nI have seen California Scrub-Jays eat from the feeder and in the wild. They look funny digging through the nuts on the feeder and spilling food everywhere while pecking and prodding at it.\n\nCalifornia Scrub-Jays are 11-12 inches (28-30 cm) long, weigh 2.8-3.5 ounces (70-100 g), and have a wingspan of about 15 inches (38 cm).\n\nCalifornia Scrub-Jays may be found hopping around or standing on a Mule Deer’s back. When they do this, they are feeding on ticks and other parasites in the fur of the deer. Most of the time, the deer seems to appreciate the help.\n\nCalifornia Scrub-Jays are not endangered and are quite common. Threats include predators like hawks, cats, owls, squirrels, raccoons, and snakes; habitat loss due to urbanization; collisions with glass; pesticides; domestic cats; climate change; wildfires; heatwaves; and diseases like West Nile Virus.\n\nPeople can help California Scrub-Jays by protecting habitat, using less glass or bird-safe windows, avoiding pesticides, watching pet cats outdoors, preventing wildfires, and supporting healthy oak woodland habitats.",
