    "commonness": "Not endangered, but populations have faced serious declines.",
    "quickFact": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw the Loggerhead Shrike.",
    "description": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw the Loggerhead Shrike. I want to tell you about this interesting (well, at least I think it’s interesting) bird because even though it looks like a songbird, it’s actually a small raptor! This bird also has a very unique eating method. That’s another reason why I like these birds.\n\nLoggerhead Shrikes eat in a way that you will think it’s one of a kind. They sit on tall shrubs, posts, or little trees to look for their prey. Then they glide down to the ground, capturing their prey. But the interesting part is when they pin their prey on thorns, barbed wires, or sharp twigs. I think it is interesting because since their talons are not strong enough, they do that so that its prey can die by itself. Loggerhead Shrikes feed on insects, arthropods, amphibians, small mammals, reptiles, and birds. In winter, they mostly eat vertebrates. Those include lizards, snakes, frogs, turtles, sparrows, goldfinches, ground squirrels, voles, mice, and shrews.\n\nLoggerhead Shrikes have gray crowns, light gray underparts, white flashes in their black wings, a black tail with a thin line of white at the very side, a thick black “mask” around their eyes on their white face, a hooked black bill, and a white belly. Loggerhead Shrikes have a length of about 8 in (20 cm)to 10 in (25 cm)and their wingspan is 13 in (33 cm).\n\nI want to share an interesting fact about the Loggerhead Shrike to you. They can carry prey as big as themselves! That’s big. Anyways. That means that they can carry prey with a length of 9 in (23 cm)! They carry the big prey they catch in their talons and they hold the smaller prey in their bills.\n\nThe biggest threat to a Loggerhead Shrike is habitat loss. Other threats include collision with vehicles, urban development, conversion of hayfields and pastureland, decimation of hedgerows, and altering of the populations of their prey by livestock grazing.\n\nSo even though Loggerhead Shrikes are not endangered, (though in the 1940s to the 2019s, they got onto the endangered species list) we still need to help them to keep them alive. So here are some ways you can help them: stop collision with vehicles, stop urban development, don’t convert hayfields or pasturelands, stop the decimation of hedgerows, and don’t alter populations of their prey. So it’s our job as humans, to keep these incredible birds well protected if we still want to admire them!",
