    "name": "Western Meadowlark",
    "documentTitle": "Meadowlark (Western Meadowlark)",
    "slug": "western-meadowlark",
    "createdAt": "2026-07-12",
    "habitat": "Open spaces, woodlands, and hunting perches",
    "size": "Length 6-10 in; wingspan about 16 in; weight 3-4 oz.",
    "color": "Yellow underparts with a black V on the chest and brown streaked upperparts.",
    "commonness": "Quite common, but breeding populations declined about 0.9% each year from 1966 to 2019.",
    "quickFact": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw the Western Meadowlark.",
    "description": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw the Western Meadowlark. They are found in the Bay Area, most likely on grasslands or dry grassy areas. They are also found in open meadows. Before I introduce the Western Meadowlarks, I will let you guess three things. Number one: In how many states is the Western Meadowlark the state bird?\n\nA: One\n\nB: Two\n\nC: Three\n\nD: Four\n\nE: Five\n\nF: Six\n\nG: Seven\n\nH: Eight\n\nThe correct answer is F. The Western Meadowlark is the state bird for six states! Let’s try another one.\n\nNumber two: In which six states is the Western Meadowlark the state bird?\n\nA: Colorado, Arizona, Oregon, Texas, Missouri, and North Carolina\n\nB: Nebraska, Washington, Montana, Tennessee, Georgia, and Utah\n\nC: Kansas, Montana, Nebraska, North Dakota, Oregon, and Wyoming\n\nD: South Dakota, Arkansas, Colorado, Minnesota, New Mexico, and Iowa\n\nE: Nevada, Kansas, Oklahoma, Virginia, Indiana, and Pennsylvania\n\nF: Idaho, Oregon, Michigan, Louisiana, New Jersey, and Maine\n\nThe correct answer is C. The Western Meadowlark is the state bird in Kansas, Montana, Nebraska, North Dakota, Oregon, and Wyoming. Let’s try one last one!\n\nNumber three: What is the only bird that beats the Western Meadowlark in the number of states in which it is the state bird and how many states is it state bird in?\n\nA: Northern Cardinal; 7\n\nB: Yellow-Breasted Chat; 8\n\nC: American Goldfinch; 7\n\nD: Evening Grosbeak; 9\n\nThe correct answer is A. The only bird that is the state bird to a greater number of states than the Western Meadowlark is the Northern Cardinal. It beats the Western Meadowlark by one state! Now that you know some fun facts about the Western Meadowlark, let’s dig in!\n\nUnlike most of the birds you have learned about in this chapter book, Western Meadowlarks eat in flocks. They forage ground in open fields, pecking the soil for insects, grain, and weed seeds. They also fly in flocks. They take off with quail-like bursts, flying with stiff wing beats, and only for short distances above a grassland, prairie, or meadow. Western Meadowlarks eat beetles, ants, cutworms, grasshoppers, and crickets. They also eat grain and weed seeds (as mentioned in the beginning of this paragraph). Western Meadowlarks have a lifespan of five to eight years. They have a length of 6 to 10 inches, and a wingspan of 16 inches. Their weight is 3 to 4 ounces.\n\nAn interesting fact about Western Meadowlarks is that when breeding, a male usually gets two mates at the same time! The female meadowlarks do all the incubating and brooding, as well as most of the feeding the young chicks.\n\nAlthough quite common, the breeding populations of Western Meadowlarks have declined about 0.9% each year between 1966 to 2019. Threats include the changing of grassland breeding and wintering habitat used for housing and agriculture, pesticides, and habitat degradation caused by invasive plant species.\n\nTo help Western Meadowlarks, you could use pesticides less, or better, stop using them! You could also get rid of invasive plant species and stop converting grasslands. If this bird goes extinct (though it currently is not close to extinction at all), then six states (Kansas, Montana, Nebraska, North Dakota, Oregon, and Wyoming) would have to change their state bird! So help keep Western Meadowlarks safe that won’t have to happen.",
