    "name": "Great-Horned Owl",
    "documentTitle": "Owl (Great-Horned Owl)",
    "slug": "great-horned-owl",
    "createdAt": "2026-07-12",
    "habitat": "Open spaces, woodlands, and hunting perches",
    "size": "Length 18.1-24.8 in; wingspan 39.8-57.1 in; weight 32.1-88.2 oz.",
    "color": "Mottled gray-brown with reddish-brown face and a white throat patch.",
    "commonness": "Very common around the world and lives in the Bay Area.",
    "quickFact": "I went to the California Raptor Center and saw the Great-Horned Owls.",
    "description": "I went to the California Raptor Center and saw the Great-Horned Owls. The California Raptor Center is not in the Bay Area, but Great-Horned Owls live in the Bay Area, and they are very common around the world. Great-Horned Owls are found on every continent except for Antarctica. They are one of the most common owls around the world. The biggest reason why I like these birds is about how silently they fly, like all owl species. The soft feathers on their wings creates less turbulence, which softens the sound. Then very soft feathers under their wings further muffles the sound. This special adaptation that other birds don’t have helps them hunt during the night without prey suspecting any danger.\n\nGreat-Horned Owls have a pretty unique way of eating. Also usually hunting during the night, they will seldom hunt in daylight. After they find the prey from a high perch, they will chase the prey over woodlands, meadows, wetlands, open water, or a lot of other habitats. They might also walk along the ground to chase their prey around bushes and other obstacles. During the night, they will just swoop down from a tree and catch their prey in their talons. Great-Horned Owls eat tiny rodents, scorpions, skunks, geese, hares, and raptors. They mostly eat birds and mammals including rabbits, mice, and American Coots. But they may also eat voles, moles, shrews, rats, gophers, chipmunks, squirrels, woodchucks, marmots, prairie dogs, bats, skunks, house cats, porcupines, ducks, loons, mergansers, grebes, rails, owls, hawks, crows, ravens, doves, and starlings. They supplement their diet with reptiles, insects, fish, invertebrates, and sometimes carrion.\n\nGreat-Horned Owls have very good hearing. Their ears are hidden behind feathers on their face. We call those feathers the facial disc. As a sound comes towards them, it will hit their facial disc. The feathers on the facial disk face towards their ears. So the sound will slide off the feathers right into their ears, which makes their hearing much better. It also helps focus on the sound and not hear all kinds of other sounds like the wind blowing, or leaves rustling, just to name a few. This unique adaptation helps them hear from underground and they are able to swoop down and capture prey as soon as it gets up above the surface of the ground. But if they need to, they may dig, following the sound to capture their prey.\n\nAnother interesting fact that only Great-Horned Owls share with all the other owl species is how they can turn their head almost all the way around! They need to do that because they can’t move their pupils. So in order to look around, they have to turn their head. And amazingly, when they turned their head around their neck bones don’t break. If you even tried to turn your head around like an owl… your neck would definitely crack, so I don’t suggest trying that. Either way it’s another interesting thing that only owls can do. All owls have more neck bones than us to help prevent their bones from cracking when they turn their heads. This adaptation might not be the best for capturing their prey, but it sure is helpful when they need to find their food.\n\nIn the mid-twenties, Great- Horned Owls were hunted, and unfortunately, some illegal hunting still remains today. They can also threaten other bird species including Peregrine Falcons and Spotted Owls, because of their prowess as predators. Great-Horned Owls are not endangered. There is only one thing you need to do to keep them thriving on planet Earth, which is not to hunt them. They are a unique species and have many interesting adaptations that help them.",
