    "documentTitle": "Pelican (American White Pelican)",
    "slug": "american-white-pelican",
    "createdAt": "2026-07-12",
    "habitat": "Wetlands, marshes, ponds, and shorelines",
    "size": "Length about 4 ft; wingspan about 9 ft.",
    "color": "Mostly white with black flight feathers and a large orange bill.",
    "commonness": "Low concern.",
    "quickFact": "I went to Baylands Nature Preserve and saw the American White Pelicans.",
    "description": "I went to Baylands Nature Preserve and saw the American White Pelicans. I like them because of their unique way of eating, which is also different from their cousin, the Brown Pelican! American White Pelicans can hold up to 3 gallons of water in their pouch! I think that’s very interesting.\n\nThe American White Pelican eats in a very unique way. Instead of diving like the Brown Pelican, they gather in flocks and herd the fish to the shallow waters where they do not have to dive. Then they fold their wings up so they do not get wet, and their head goes below and above, below and above, below and above the surface of the water, scooping up little fish. Once they fill their pouch, they contract the pouch muscles to drain out all the water before swallowing the prey whole.\n\nAmerican White Pelicans have yellow-orange beaks, a white body, and white and black underwings. Their feet are also yellow-orange, though slightly more orange than their beaks. They also have a thin circle of yellow around their eyes, which connects to their beaks. The American White Pelican has a length of about 4 feet and a wingspan of approximately 9 feet.\n\nAmerican White Pelican chicks can crawl when they are 1 to 2 weeks old! Once they are 3 weeks old, they can walk without their body touching the ground and swim as soon as they touch water. The chicks that are older go on to learn how to run, flapping their wings while running, and then when they are 9 to 10 weeks of age, flying.\n\nOne of the major threats to the American White Pelicans is humans foraging their breeding grounds. Since they depend on shallow waters to catch their prey, flooding has been a problem for them too. Another threat is pollution. Littering can also affect them.\n\nAmerican White Pelicans are in low concern, though we still have to help them. So, one tip is never, ever feed them, or really just don’t feed wildlife. If you do, then they will come to where humans live which makes it easier for them to get hurt because there is more litter there. Well, that also means don’t litter! Wind, rain, and water can bring litter all over the place, and animals could get really injured if they get stuck. People should also stop polluting. Pollution has been affecting all wildlife, not only the American White Pelican. This will help all animals and maybe even some plants!",
