    "size": "Length 7.9-11 in.",
    "color": "Gray-brown upperparts, warm orange breast, dark head, and white eye arcs.",
    "commonness": "Not endangered; global breeding population about 370 million.",
    "quickFact": "I’ve seen American Robins in my backyard.",
    "description": "I’ve seen American Robins in my backyard. They usually stay on the lawn, looking for worms to eat. Before we learn more about this species, a fun fact is that these robins eat different foods during different times of the day! They eat earthworms in the morning and more fruit later in the day. Because they feed on lawns a lot, they are vulnerable to pesticide poisoning. Because of this, they can easily indicate when there is chemical pollution. Let’s learn some more!\n\nAmerican Robins run a few steps and then stop abruptly when foraging on the ground. When in the long grass, they will hop or fly slightly above the ground with slow, powerful wingbeats. They usually stare motionlessly at the ground with their head cocked to one side. This method is how they find most worms. The robins may also fight over worms that others have caught so that they don’t have to catch one themselves. American Robins eat earthworms and insects as well as some snails mainly during the spring and summer. They have rarely been found eating shrews, small snakes, and aquatic insects. The fruits they eat include chokecherries, hawthorn, dogwood, sumac fruits, and juniper berries. Some scientists think that the robins choose which fruits to eat by finding the ones with bugs in it.\n\nAdults are 7.9-11 inches (20-28 centimeters) long. They weigh 2.7-3 ounces (77-85 grams), about the same weight as three AA batteries. Their wingspan ranges from 12.2-15.8 inches (31-40 centimeters) in length. Their size is similar to a Spotted Towhee or a Red-Winged Blackbird.\n\nAn interesting fact about the American Robin is that their roosts can be HUGE. During the winter, there can be a quarter-million robins in just one roost! In summer, while the females sleep in their nests, the males gather together at the roost. When the robin chicks become independent, they join the males. But the female adults only join the males and go to the roosts after they finish nesting.\n\nAmerican Robins are not endangered. Their population increased by 0.13% each year from 1966 to 2019! Their global breeding population is at about 370 million. Threats include pesticides (since they often forage on lawns) and outdoor cats eating them. Others include collisions with windows, communication towers, cars, and other common hazards.\n\nEven though American Robins are at low concern, we still have to protect them if we want them to keep thriving! You can help by using less pesticides and making sure your cat -if you have one- doesn’t kill an American Robin (or even better, any bird) when it is let outside. Ways to help with collisions are to use less windows and communication towers and BE CAREFUL WHEN YOU DRIVE!!! This may not only help American Robins but also other species of birds and maybe even animals!",
