    "quickFact": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw the Sandhill Cranes.",
    "description": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw the Sandhill Cranes. One fact about Sandhill Cranes is that they have a bald head. They have them because it’s a sign of maturity for these birds. That is one interesting fact about them. Another fact is that they can get out of their nest 8 hours after they hatch, capable of swimming! That’s like 8 hours after you’re born, you can safely play outside while being able to walk! Incredible!\n\nSandhill Cranes are omnivores and eat seeds, grains, snails, small vertebrates, berries, invertebrates, small mammals, nestling birds, reptiles, amphibians, tubers, and fish. They will also eat plants that grow in and near the water. To eat fish, they will walk around in the water and when they find a fish, they will strike. And don’t be surprised when you see a Sandhill Crane digging. They catch insects like that. They will dig to find the insects, then they will catch them.\n\nSandhill Cranes breed for life. Most will breed at or before the age of 2, but some may not breed until 7 years old! That is a pretty old age for a Sandhill Crane to start breeding!\n\nSandhill Cranes are a low concern species, increasing a bit more than 4% each year. But unfortunately, the Mississippi Sandhill Crane is endangered. Another isolated part of Florida is of concern, but is not endangered yet. There is not much you need to do to help protect the Sandhill Crane, for the number of Sandhill Cranes are slowly increasing. The Sandhill Crane is a unique bird that deserves to be protected!",
