    "quickFact": "I went to Shoreline Park and saw the Turkey Vultures.",
    "description": "I went to Shoreline Park and saw the Turkey Vultures. They are unique because they have bald heads. Have you ever wondered why they have bald heads? Well, you’ll learn that in this chapter! It is actually pretty simple. I’ll let you take a guess.\n\nA: they just have bald heads\n\nB: because they don’t want blood to cover their feathers when they fight\n\nC: because they don’t want to get blood on their feathers when they eat\n\nD: B and C\n\nE: None of the above\n\nThe correct answer is C. They don’t want to get blood on their feathers when they eat! That is very interesting to me. Now, it is time I introduce you to the unique bird: the Turkey Vultures!\n\nTurkey Vultures rarely hunt. They usually steal food instead. And then, like most other raptors, they will tear up their food and eat it. The biggest, strongest vultures will eat first. The small and skinny ones have to wait to eat the scraps at the end.\n\nNow, as you know from the beginning, Turkey Vultures have bald heads. And I want to remind you that this is because they do not want to get blood on their feathers when they eat. Another cool thing about them is this: when a bird, animal, or a human comes near, they will vomit on them! Despite what they eat, this may be a strong weapon. So I’m warning you, don’t go too near to a Turkey Vulture.\n\nTurkey Vultures are of low concern. Threats include pesticides. The biggest threat towards a Turkey Vulture is food poisoning. Since a Turkey Vulture's main diet is rotten food, poisoning will make them sick and may lead to death. Other threats include trapping and killing.\n\nYet not endangered, Turkey Vultures still deserve to be protected. To help, please don’t poison their food. Don’t trap them or kill them either. Turkey Vultures are very unique and we need to keep them safe, and I hope you help too!",
    "mapNote": "Use your map notes for Turkey Vulture here.",
