    "name": "Common Murre",
    "documentTitle": "Uria aalge (Common Murre)",
    "slug": "common-murre",
    "createdAt": "2026-07-12",
    "habitat": "Coastal waters and rocky nesting areas",
    "size": "Length 38-43 cm; wingspan 64-71 cm; weight 800-1,125 g.",
    "color": "Dark brownish head and upperparts with white breast and belly.",
    "commonness": "Not treated as endangered in the essay, but faces hunting and other pressures.",
    "quickFact": "A bird starting with the letter U is hard to find, so instead, I used the scientific name of a Common Murre: Uria aalge.",
    "description": "A bird starting with the letter U is hard to find, so instead, I used the scientific name of a Common Murre: Uria aalge. This is why they are called Uria aalge: The word Uria comes from the Greek word “ourein” (οὐρέω), which means to dive. This reflects on the bird's diving skills. The word “aalge” is the old Danish word of auk, the family it is in. The Common Murre can also be called the Common Guillemot. These birds are most likely seen at places like Devil’s Rock and Farallon Islands and Point Reyes in the early morning and late afternoon. They are also best found from spring to summer. Let’s dive deeper so we can learn more about these eggcellent birds (Get it?)!\n\nCommon Murres eat by diving deep into the water and catching prey in their bill. They “fly” through the water and use their wings to navigate. Once a Common Murre dived as much as 591 feet, but most murres dive 66-146 feet. Common Murres also forage in flocks. Rockfish, pollock, arctic cod, saffron cod, tom cod, surfperch, sandlance, sculpin, hake, greenling, capelin, herring, smelt, anchovy, and sardine are what they usually eat in the Pacific. In the Atlantic, they take capelin, sandlance, shad, menhaden, flounder, lanternfish, and Atlantic cod. Other prey include amphipods, krill, and marine worms. They may also eat squid and octopus especially in the nonbreeding season.\n\nCommon Murres have a length of 38 - 43 cm, a wingspan of 64 - 71 cm, and weigh 800 - 1,125 grams. Their size is very similar to the Razorbill (another seabird) and the Thick-Billed Murre. They are also slightly bigger than a Tufted Puffin. Mallards have a longer length and wingspan but have similar weight to the Common Murre.\n\nAn interesting fact about the Common Murre is that they lay their eggs so that they point in a direction that will make the egg roll in a circle instead of falling off the cliff. They are also shaped like a pear, which helps. Smart, right?\n\nAnother fact is that even though Common Murres look like penguins and are even nicknamed “flying penguins” because they look like them but can fly, they aren’t closely related to penguins. Murres are in a family called the Alcidae (with auks, razorbills, puffins, auklets, murrelets, and guillemots) when penguins are in a family called the Sphenicidae. Murres are in the Charadriiformes order when penguins are in the Spheniciformes order. Murres also live in the Northern Hemisphere when penguins live in the Southern Hemisphere.\n\nAlso, even though Common Murres are called Common Guillemots too, they are not guillemots. Guillemots are a different species than a murre but the two are in the same family (the auk family). Guillemots are mostly black but have white patches under their wings which is easy to differentiate from murres, who have white breasts and bellies and a dark brownish tanish head and back.\n\nCommon Murres are common, which makes sense due to their name: Common Murres. In Canada, 100,000 individual murres are hunted annually. They are also hunted in Greenland and the Faroe Islands. Sad. Other threats include climate change, affecting the water temperatures and reducing the availability of prey they have, and oil spilling. Oil pollution also is part of the “prey species for Common Murres are reducing” problem. Another threat is over fishing, doing the same as the previous two. A last threat is mammalian predators, such as foxes. Thankfully, it has stopped now, but people used to take their eggs as food. Don’t Common Murres already have enough difficulties?\n\nYou can help keep Common Murres at their current high population by encouraging others to cease climate change. This is a MASSIVE problem for not only murres, but all other animals, plants, and even us! We want to keep our planet healthy, just like we try to keep ourselves healthy. You can also not spill oil into the ocean. Try to reduce the hunting of this species and when you see trash, pick it up to prevent further pollution. Remember: THERE ARE TRASH CANS FOR A REASON!!! USE THEM AND DON’T LITTER!!! Unfortunately, we can’t do much about the predators they have, unless we kill off most of the foxes, but then the foxes would be endangered, and it would all be pointless. Don’t lose hope yet, though! There’s one more thing you can do: Share your knowledge about this fascinating bird so others can help preserve it too! See you in the next chapter!",
