    "size": "Length 5.1-5.5 in; height 3.1 in; wingspan 9.4-9.8 in.",
    "color": "Males are bright red/orange with dark wings; females are brownish with pale underparts.",
    "commonness": "Pretty common; desert species.",
    "quickFact": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw a Vermilion Flycatcher.",
    "description": "I went to Merced National Wildlife Refuge and saw a Vermilion Flycatcher. One interesting fact about the Vermilion Flycatcher is that its genus name is Pyrocephalus, which means “fire-headed.” That’s because of the vermilion feathers atop their heads, which also gives them their name: Vermilion Flycatcher. Now that you know how Vermilion Flycatchers got their name, let’s dig (or more like fly) in!\n\nVermilion Flycatchers, like all other flycatchers, capture their prey on their wing or by suddenly flying out from an exposed perch. These flights are short and direct, and they often swoop back in a circle, returning to the same perch. Vermilion Flycatchers usually feed within the range of 10 feet off ground. They carry prey back to the perch, then will whack it against the perch. That makes their prey more soft before eating. Vermilion Flycatchers eat bugs such as grasshoppers, butterflies, honey bees, beetles, and crickets. A Vermilion Flycatcher is quite small. They have a length of 5.1 to 5.5 inches, a height of 3.1 inches, and a wingspan of 9.4 to 9.8 inches. They weigh 0.39 to 0.49 ounces. They also have a lifespan of 4 to 5 years.\n\nOne interesting fact about Vermilion Flycatchers is that when a male Vermilion Flycatcher courts a female one, the male one brings a gift! The gift is usually a butterfly or some other type of flashy insect. That’s a unique thing that Vermilion Flycatchers do.\n\nVermilion Flycatchers are pretty common. During 1969 to 2015, their population has been quite stable. In 2016, it was reported that it was estimated that the breeding population of Vermilion Flycatchers was at 560,000. As a desert specie, Vermilion Flycatchers are sensitive to impacts from land development and human water use. Another threat is habitat destruction. Excessive groundwater pumping may also destroy the desert riparian habitats that the Vermilion Flycatcher and other desert species rely on.\n\nTo help Vermilion Flycatchers, you can stop land development and don’t pump groundwater, or at least do it less. That will help keep their habitat safe. Although Vermilion Flycatchers are very far from extinction, they still deserve to be protected!",
