    "color": "Bright blue head, wings, plumage, and tail; orange chest; white belly.",
    "commonness": "Pretty common.",
    "quickFact": "I went to Shoreline Park and saw the Western Bluebirds.",
    "description": "I went to Shoreline Park and saw the Western Bluebirds. Most of them were sitting on the trees, and some were on the ground. Western Bluebirds are cute little songbirds with a bright blue head, wings, plumage, and tail, an orange chest, and a white belly.\n\nWestern Bluebirds don’t really have a unique way of eating. As usual, they will just catch their prey, rather in the air or from the ground. But they will particularly catch ground-dwelling insects such as grasshoppers, ants, beetles, spiders, caterpillars, wasps, pill bugs, and snails. During the winter, they will change their diet to fruits and seeds. Those include elderberries, grapes, mistletoes, raspberries, serviceberries, sumacs, blackberries, chokecherries, junipers, and even poison oak!\n\nLike many other birds, Western Bluebirds live in tree cavities. But their bills are not made for packing in the wood. So, they rely on woodpeckers to help them make their homes. And though they look very gentle, they are very aggressive with their territory. Male rivals may grab each other’s legs, tumble to the ground, pin their opponent, stand over them, or jab them with their bills!\n\nWestern Bluebirds are pretty common. Their biggest threats include habitat loss, more logging, more wildfires, and also development and grazing. Even in wooded areas, people still remove dead trees, making it more difficult for Western Bluebirds to nest. Other aggressive birds like House Sparrows and European Starlings take over Western Bluebirds nest sites that Western Bluebirds might otherwise use. So to protect Western Bluebirds, don’t log or remove dead trees. You can also plant more trees for them to live in. Without being able to nest, Western Bluebirds might go extinct (though there’s no sign of extinction today)! We can work together to keep Western Bluebirds thriving!",
