    "name": "Yellow Warbler",
    "documentTitle": "Yellow Warbler",
    "slug": "yellow-warbler",
    "createdAt": "2026-07-12",
    "habitat": "Bay Area parks, neighborhoods, woodlands, and fields",
    "size": "Length 4.7-5.1 in; wingspan 6.3-7.9 in; weight 0.3-0.4 oz.",
    "color": "Yellow songbird; males often show rusty streaking on the chest.",
    "commonness": "Very numerous in the Bay Area and North America, though declined about 20% from 1966 to 2019.",
    "quickFact": "It’s not easy being a small bird.",
    "description": "It’s not easy being a small bird. In fact, it’s dangerous! Sometimes, Yellow Warblers are found tangled in an orb weaver spider’s web! Their predators include garter snakes, blue racers (also a type of snake), red squirrels and other big rodents, American Crows, Blue Jays, racoons, weasels, skunks, foxes, cats, and even some hawks and owls! I thought this was very interesting (and sad) for I didn't know that squirrels, crows, jays, or weasels ate small birds. Come and learn more about this small songbird.\n\nYellow Warblers eat insects that they pick from foliage or capture on short flights or while hovering to reach leaves. They mostly forage along slender branches of shrubs of small trees where there are a lot of insects. They may also look on or under leaves. They also usually feed near water since lots of insects live near water. Common prey include midges, caterpillars, beetles, small spiders, moths, mosquitos, damselflies, leafhoppers and wasps. They also might eat bits of fruit, especially in the winter.\n\nYellow Warblers are about 4.7 to 5.1 inches (12 to 13 cm) in length and have a wingspan of 6.3 to 7.9 inches (16 to 20 cm). They weigh between 0.3 and 0.4 ounces (9 and 11 grams). Their size is similar to an American Redstart or a Palm Warbler.\n\nDid you know that Brown-Headed Cowbirds will often parasize (meaning the female cowbird will lay her eggs into the warbler's nest so she doesn’t have to raise the chicks herself) the nest of Yellow Warblers (and also other species of birds in case you're wondering)? However, because the warbler can recognize the different eggs (usually), it will build a new nest directly on top of the parasitized one when this happens, sometimes resulting in nests with up to six tiers. And the Yellow Warblers have an alarm for when a Brown-Headed Cowbird is nearby! Their ‘seet’ call is actually a warning.\n\nYellow Warblers are very numerous not just in the Bay Area but also in all of North America. Unfortunately, their population declined about 0.4% per year for a total decline of about 20% from 1966 to 2019. But they are still very common and their global breeding population is around 97 million. Despite this, we still have to protect them because an estimated 2.25 to 4.5 million Yellow Warblers die each year from collisions alone! Other threats include grazing in rangelands, especially by creeks near stands of willow trees because it makes it harder for them to find a good nesting spot then. Brown-Headed Cowbirds are also a problem since they (as I mentioned before) lay their eggs in Yellow Warbler’s nests. That can reduce nesting success.\n\nYou can still help Yellow Warblers by building with less glass and trying to keep grazing out of where Yellow Warblers would nest. But unfortunately, we can do nothing about the Brown-Headed Cowbirds. Just doing the first two would still help a lot! Let’s try to keep this species thriving!",
