    "quickFact": "Since a bird starting with Z is hard to find, I used the scientific name of a White-Crowned Sparrow: Zonotrichia leucophrys.",
    "description": "Since a bird starting with Z is hard to find, I used the scientific name of a White-Crowned Sparrow: Zonotrichia leucophrys. Zono comes from the Greek word “zone” (ζώνη) and trichia comes from the Greek word “thrix” (θρίξ). Since \"zone\" means band and “thrix” means hair, Zonothricia means bands in hair, in this case describing the white stripes they have. The word leucophrys also originates in the Greek. Leuc comes from the Greek word leukos (λευκός) which means white. The other part of the word (ophrys) comes from the Greek word ophrys (ὀφρῦς) and means eyebrow. So leucophrys means white eyebrow, and just like Zonothricia, it also describes the white stripes over their eyes. Even though I’ve never seen one of these myself (yet), they are still common in the Bay Area and can mostly be seen in the winter and spring, which is from late September to April. Now that you know how this bird got its scientific name and when you can find it, let’s learn even more!\n\nWhite-Crowneed Sparrows eat by hopping across the ground in shrubs and bushes. They will also “double-scratch”, which is when they hop backwards to turn over leaves before hoping forward again with a pounce. Along with that, they will peck at visible bugs and seeds, or fly up from a low perch or the ground to catch an insect in mid-air. They may eat small berries, catkins, and other vegetation on perches too. They will eat seeds, weeds, small buds, ragweeds, pigweeds, catkin, and grasses. You may also see them eating bugs including caterpillars, wasps, and beetles during the summertime. They also eat grain like oats, corn, wheat, and barley along with fruits like elderberries and blackberries.\n\nAn interesting fact about White-Crowned Sparrows is that they will share their territory with Fox Sparrows but chase away Dark-Eyed Juncos and Chipping Sparrows. Also, don’t underestimate these birds. They may be tiny but one was tracked down as it migrated and every day it traveled about 300 miles! It would take us about 10 to 20 days to walk 300 miles (if we stopped to sleep)!\n\nWhite-Crowned Sparrows have a length of 15–16 cm (5.9–6.3 inches). Females weigh approximately 25.5 grams (0.9 oz) as a male weighs about 28 grams (1.0 oz). They have a wingspan of 8.3 inches to 9.4 inches (21–24 cm). They are slightly larger than a Song Sparrow and House Sparrows weigh slightly more than them.\n\nWhite-Crowned Sparrows are very common and widespread with no declines or inclines. Their population held steady really well between 1966 and 2019 and still is now. But they still have threats that include habitat loss caused by logging, agriculture, shrub succession, urbanization, and wildfires. Climate change is affecting the succession of their eggs and fledglings, especially in the tundra or shrubland nests. The exposure of pesticides and chemicals is a threat they share with other birds. These bad chemicals can delay migrations and make them lose a lot of weight, which is bad for them. Predators like snakes, hawks, owls, raccoons, and cats, both domestic and wild, also contribute. Lastly, collisions with windows and cars also threatens them.\n\nTheir population remains balanced because they can eat many different foods from bugs and insects to berries and fruit to grain, seeds, and other vegetation. They also have many habitats like tundra, boreal, urban backyards, and areas with lots of shrubs. They are also protected by law.\n\nWays you can help are to preserve early-succession shrubs, reduce the use of pesticides and other harmful chemicals, try to keep your cat away from any birds, or just keep them indoors (if you have a cat), build with less windows and BE CAREFUL WHEN YOU ARE DRIVING!!!!! You can also try to stop climate change by using less plastic, turning off lights as often as possible, eating less meat, using more electrical vehicles, bike and walk more, and also try not to waste. Reducing the use of fossil fuels is another way you can help. You can also prevent wildfires by keeping campfires under control, not to throw cigarettes and matches on the ground, and being careful when setting off firecrackers and fireworks, getting rid of dry leaves, and trimming trees. That way, you can help in keeping the White-Crowned Sparrow’s population as stable as it has always been!",
